        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>ALMAs exquisite sensitivity is necessary in order to discover emission from molecular gas in NGC4636; to date, no reliable detection of CO emission from the filamentary optical line emitting nebula around NGC4636 is available. However, our detection of [CII] line emission with Herschel PACS gives us firm reason to expect the presence of molecular gas in this region. As shown below, the expected detection level is below the current CO upper limits.

The peak [CII] flux measured with Herschel PACS is 13 Jy, with a line width of 361 km/s (Werner et al. 2013). If the ionization mechanism in the filamentary gas surrounding NGC4636 and the central group galaxy NGC5044 is the same, then using the [CII] to CO(2-1) flux ratio measured in NGC5044 (Werner et al. 2013b) and assuming a CO(3-2)/CO(2-1) ratio of 2 yields an expected peak flux density of 5.2 mJy. Because the Halpha/[CII] flux ratio is fairly uniform in NGC5044, we can use an Halpha map to simulate the expected CO emission.

The best high resolution image of the nebula is an Halpha+[NII] image from the SOAR telescope, which also shows a good agreement with the [CII] flux distribution. We rescaled this Halpha image to a range of expected peak fluxes and performed a series of simulations using CASAs simobserve and simanalyze tools. Based on these simulations, we request a target RMS sensitivity of 0.285 mJy per beam per 30 km/sec (binned) channel, which can be reached in 3 hours on source.  

In the most likely scenario that the [CII] to CO flux conversion is similar to that measured in NGC 5044, we will be able to sample the filament along the SE loop (the faintest feature we aim to study in detail) in 30 km/s resolution elements with a S/N of 5. However, the uncertainty in the flux conversion between [CII] and CO is potentially large. This ratio is about a factor of 4 smaller in normal galaxies and Galactic molecular clouds (amounting to a higher CO flux for a fixed [CII] line intensity) than in starburst galaxies and Galactic star-forming regions (Crawford et al. 1985; Stacey et al. 1991). Even in the most pessimistic scenario that the [CII] to CO is among the highest values ever measured in any other galaxy, we will still detect the bright central part of NGC4636 with a S/N of at least 10 per 30 km/sec velocity element.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We chose the high spectral resolution baseband centered on the sky frequency of the redshifted CO(3-2) line. We will use the widest available spectral window (1875 MHz) which will enable us to detect all the outflowing/inflowing gas clouds and gives us a good continuum baseline. To lower the data rate, we have opted to bin the data by a factor of 4. This will provide us a velocity resolution of 1.6 km/s, which is sufficient for the proposed science. For the data analysis, we will increase this binning depending on the strength of the signal until an appropriate signal to noise is reached.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The selected angular resolution will allow us to probe spatial scales of about one-seventh of the sphere of influence of the central SMBH and half of the Bondi accretion radius. Based on the existing Halpha map, the cold gas nebula mainly consists of narrow filaments up to 2.5 arcseconds wide, therefore we expect to recover the entire CO-flux of the source in the proposed configuration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
